-- Japanese Exporters Are Likely to Sell Euro Versus Yen, Nikkei Reports
-- Ron Harui
-- 2010-06-29T01:22:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-29/japanese-exporters-are-likely-to-sell-euro-versus-yen-nikkei-reports.html

          
          
             Japanese exporters are likely to
sell euros for yen, pushing the 16-nation common currency down
further, Nikkei English News reported, without saying how it
obtained the information.  
 Since the euroâ€™s slide in May, Japanese companies have
avoided selling the euro-denominated income they received from
exports to Europe, the Nikkei reported. As their holdings of
euros have continued to increase even as the single currency
shows few signs of a rebound, the companies may begin to sell
the euro at a loss, the Nikkei said.  
 Exporters had assumed a euro-yen exchange rate of between
120 and 125, so their earnings would be lower than expected if
they sell euros at this time, the Nikkei reported.  
